## Tip 1: Your model relationships are everything!

Well not everything, but you get my gist. If your model realtionships are set up correctly ActiveRecord makes your life smooth as butter. I realized that concept ,14 hours of work into my project, when I was staring at this line of Active Record Query, that I managed to smash together on my keyboard.

```
<% MemoryDeck.joins(:user).where("user_id = ?", params[:user_id]).group("title").each  do |deck| %>
            <li><%= link_to deck.title, memory_deck_path(deck)  %></li>
          <% end %>
```

I want to take a minute and aknowledge how beautiful that line is. Bound paramaters, joins, group by what?! On a side note: If anybody has any questions about this feel free to reach out to me via linkedin. https://www.linkedin.com/in/nico-roulston-47852548/ . In plain english I am returning Memory decks that are associated with the current user, and then grouping those decks by title. I then take those groups and make the assumption that they are all the same deck and create anchor links listed out for the client(browser). 


### Meet my initial plan
<img src="data:image/png;base64," style="cursor:pointer;max-width:100%;" onclick="(function(img){if(img.wnd!=null&&!img.wnd.closed){img.wnd.focus();}else{var r=function(evt){if(evt.data=='ready'&&evt.source==img.wnd){img.wnd.postMessage(decodeURIComponent(img.getAttribute('src')),'*');window.removeEventListener('message',r);}};window.addEventListener('message',r);img.wnd=window.open('https://viewer.diagrams.net/?client=1&edit=_blank');}})(this);"/>

A user can have many decks, a deck can only have one user, a deck can have one card, and a card can have many decks. What seemed like a basic many to many relationship never sat right with me. What actually happened was the proverbial memory deck was created every single time I created a card, and thus it appeared as if there was dupliate decks littering my database, and this was with only one deck seeded into my database. The domain model of a deck only holding one card didn't fit the real world example of a deck holding many cards. Looking back I should have gone with my gut feeling from the start, and I would have avoided having to write the aformentioned gorgeous ActiveRecord query. 


Honestly that was way to much work. So I went back to the drawing board.

### The redesign

<img src="data:image/png;base64," style="cursor:pointer;max-width:100%;" onclick="(function(img){if(img.wnd!=null&&!img.wnd.closed){img.wnd.focus();}else{var r=function(evt){if(evt.data=='ready'&&evt.source==img.wnd){img.wnd.postMessage(decodeURIComponent(img.getAttribute('src')),'*');window.removeEventListener('message',r);}};window.addEventListener('message',r);img.wnd=window.open('https://viewer.diagrams.net/?client=1&edit=_blank');}})(this);"/>

With the idea in mind that a deck should be able to have many cards, and a card could potentially be shared with many different decks I came up with the above. I also knew that I wanted to be able to ask a card who it's users were. Most importantly I wanted to use Active Records relationship methods instead of the Active Record Query I wrote:

```
<% MemoryDeck.joins(:user).where("user_id = ?", params[:user_id]).group("title").each  do |deck| %>
            <li><%= link_to deck.title, memory_deck_path(deck)  %></li>
          <% end %>
```

Became:

```
<% current_user.memory_decks.each do |deck| %>
    <p><%= link_to deck.title, memory_deck_path(deck)  %></p>
  <% end %>
```


I dare say that the second iteration is just as pretty if not more so. The abstraction of asking a current user what it's memory decks are is the butter of ActiveRecord. The list goes on where I discovered that establishing a relationship between models made the future development of my code easier than using ActiveRecord queries. 

## Tip 2: Don't forget about the concepts taught before.

For the past 8 weeks at Flatiron I have lived and breathed CRUD(Create,read,update,delete). After awhile I forgot that there was so much more that I could do with an App. I just had to make my past knowledge work within the Ruby on Rails Framework. Luckily for me DHH has been doing this far longer than I have. 

In my Spaced Repetition note card app that I was building I realized I would need to start working with array objects again. The keyword being an object, because everything in rails is an object. You will see why this is important in a second. My first a idea was to create class variables in my models, but that didn't sit right with me. Why was it a Class's job to keep track of each instance/records information. It should be the job of the instance. Next came instance variables, but that didn't sit right with me either. Everytime I pulled that instance/record out of the database I would have to reassign whatever array I wanted to the instance to know about it. In my head I knew that the right answer was to assign the array object to an instances/records attribute. After multiple failed attempts of doing it myself, google came to the rescue. I discovered the macro serialize. To keep it simple serialize makes it possible to store objects in the database. Arrays are objects. So when you use the macro it converts the object in to a string that gets stored in the records, and when you retrieve the object the macro converts it back from a string into a PORO(plain old ruby object).

As always you can check out how it all works at my [Github repository](https://github.com/Nroulston/level_up_learning).

Check out the youtube [demo](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rxlac4YW-eQ&list=PLELHuMLUwT4g6BprJ4i979IIoQtchnfWI&index=4&t=30s) to see how the product flows
